  "title": "Book Sprint",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ce887b6d1a0cd82f",
      "text": "Book sprints - writing together on short notice "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c87d96e6a820603a",
      "text": "The idea of \"book sprints\" was developed as a group to tackle things that would otherwise be left undone and not written down: Experts meet together at a round table for a few days and write documentation on software codes or manuals for software applications (Kean, 2012). These \"sprints\", in the sense of closely timed, collaborative work processes, have long been common in other contexts and have been borrowed from them. Zennaro et al. (2013) explain in particular the relationship to agile software development according to SCRUM, in which sprints represent a central element (Schwaber & Beedle, 2002)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4cd6d5ed5c1a4146",
      "text": "Up to now, booksprints have rarely been carried out in the context of universities. Possible reasons could be that detailed quality assurance and intensive engagement with the topics are difficult to realize in a booksprint. Nevertheless, individual cases showed that this seems to be possible. The following study is therefore devoted to the question: How is it possible to publish texts together in short periods of time in the context of universities?"
    }
